Definition 3.26. Let $n\geq 1$ be an integer, and $\mathcal{U}$ be an $n$-theory enriched in groupoids. Let $m\geq 0$ and $\ell\geq 1$ be integers. Then, for an $\ell$-categorified $\mathcal{U}$-graded $m$-theory $\mathcal{X}$, we denote by $\Theta_{m}\mathcal{X}$, the ($\ell-1$)-categorified $\mathcal{U}$-graded ($m+1$)-theory represented by $\mathcal{X}$, namely, obtained by replacing the structure functors of $\mathcal{X}$ by the bimodules/distributors/profunctors corepresented by them.
Definition 1.7. Let $n\geq 2$ be an integer. A symmetric $n$-theory $\mathcal{U}$ (which will often be called simply an “$n$-theory”) enriched in a symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{A}$, consists of data of the forms specified below as ($0$), ($1$), ($2$) (or just $(0)$, $(1)$ if $n=2$), “($k$)” for every integer $k$ such that $3\leq k\leq n-1$, ($n$), ($n+1$), ($n+2$), and “($n+\ell$)” for every integer $\ell\geq 3$. We refer to a multicategory enriched in $\mathcal{A}$ also as a (symmetric) $1$-theory enriched in $\mathcal{A}$. We refer to a commutative algebra in $\mathcal{A}$ also as a (symmetric) $0$-theory (“enriched”) in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 3.8. Let $n\geq 1$ be an integer, and let $\mathcal{U}$ be an $n$-theory enriched in groupoids. Then a $\mathcal{U}$-graded $n$-theory $\mathcal{X}$ enriched in a multicategory $\mathcal{M}$ consists of data of the forms specified below as ($0$) and ($1$) (or just ($0$) if $n=2$), “($k$)” for every integer $k$ such that $2\leq k\leq n-2$, ($n-1$), ($n$), ($n+1$), and ($\infty$).
Definition 4.25. Let • $n\geq 0$ be an integer, and $\mathcal{U}$ be an $n$-theory enriched in groupoids with the unique functor $\Delta\colon\mathcal{U}\to{\boldsymbol{1}}^{n}_{\mathrm{Com}}$, • $m\geq 0$ be an integer, and $\mathcal{T},\mathcal{J}$ be $\mathcal{U}$-graded ($m+1$)-theory enriched in groupoids, • $k$ be an integer such that $0\leq k\leq m+1$, and $\mathcal{A}$ be a symmetric monoidal $k$-category, • $F\colon\mathcal{T}\to\Delta^{*}\mathbb{B}^{m+1-k}\Theta^{k}_{0}\mathcal{A}$ and $G\colon\mathcal{J}\to\Delta^{*}\mathbb{B}^{m-k+1}\Theta^{k}_{0}\mathcal{A}$ be functors of $\mathcal{U}$-graded ($m+1$)-theories. For these, let $P\colon\Delta_{!}\Theta^{N}_{m+1}\mathcal{T}\to\Theta^{N}_{n}\mathcal{U}$ (where $N:=\max\{m+1,n\}$) and $\widetilde{Q}\colon P_{!}P^{*}\mathcal{J}\to\mathcal{T}$ be the respective projections, and $\widetilde{P}\colon P_{!}P^{*}\mathcal{J}\to\mathcal{J}$ be the counit for the adjunction. Then we define the $\mathcal{T}$-graded ($m+1$)-theory $\mathrm{Fun}\big{(}(\mathcal{T},F),(\mathcal{J},G)\big{)}$ as $\widetilde{Q}_{!}\mathrm{Fun}(F\widetilde{Q},G\widetilde{P})$, where $F\widetilde{Q},G\widetilde{P}\colon\Delta_{!}\Theta^{N}_{m+1}P_{!}P^{*}% \mathcal{J}\longrightarrow\Theta^{N}_{m-k+1}\mathbb{B}^{m-k+1}\mathcal{A}$ are the indicated functors of symmetric $N$-theories.
Definition 3.1. Let $n\geq 2$ be an integer, and let $\mathcal{U}$ be an unenriched $n$-theory. Then a $\mathcal{U}$-algebra $\mathcal{X}$ enriched in a multicategory $\mathcal{M}$ consists of data of the forms specified below as ($0$) and ($1$) (or just ($0$) if $n=2$), “($k$)” for every integer $k$ such that $2\leq k\leq n-2$, ($n-1$), ($n$) and ($\infty$).
Definition 3.19. Let $A$ be a $0$-theory in groupoids, i.e., a commutative monoid. Then an $A$-graded $0$-theory is a $\Theta_{0}A$-algebra.
Definition 2.2. Let $n\geq 2$ be an integer. We say that an $n$-theory as defined in Definition 1.7, as $n$-tuply coloured. Let $m$ be an integer such that $1\leq m\leq n-1$. Then a (symmetric) $m$-tuply coloured $n$-theory $\mathcal{U}$ enriched in a symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{A}$, consists of data of the forms specified below as ($n-m$), “($k$)” for every integer $k$ such that $n-m+1\leq k\leq n-1$, ($n$), ($n+1$) and ($\infty$).
Definition 4.5 (cf. [14, Definition 3.2]). Let $R$ be a commutative ring and $E^{\bullet}$ a complex of $R$-modules. The cohomological support of $E^{\bullet}$ is the subspace $\operatorname{Supph}(E^{\bullet})\subseteq\operatorname{Spec}R$ of those prime ideals $\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{Spec}R$ at which the complex $E_{\mathfrak{p}}^{\bullet}$ of $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$-modules is not acyclic.
Definition 3.1 ([7, Definition 1]). A local homomorphism $f\colon(R,\mathfrak{m})\rightarrow(S,\mathfrak{n})$ of Noetherian local rings is said to be of finite length if the ideal $f(\mathfrak{m})S$ is $\mathfrak{n}$-primary, or equivalently, if the closed fiber of $f$ is of dimension zero. These conditions are also equivalent to the statement that if $\mathfrak{p}$ is a prime ideal of $S$ such that $f^{-1}(\mathfrak{p})=\mathfrak{m}$, then $\mathfrak{p}=\mathfrak{n}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $R$ be a commutative ring and let $D(R)$ denote the derived category of the category of $R$-modules. A strictly perfect complex on $R$ is a bounded complex of projective $R$-modules of finite type. The category of perfect complexes over $R$, which we will denote by $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$, is the full subcategory of $D(R)$ consisting of all complexes that are quasi-isomorphic to a strictly perfect complex on $R$.
Definition 2.3 ([3, Definition 2.5]). Let $F\colon\mathcal{D}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ be an exact (triangulated) endofunctor of a triangulated category $\mathcal{D}$ with a generator $G$. The entropy of $F$ is the function $h_{t}(F)\colon\mathbb{R}\rightarrow[-\infty,+\infty)$ of $t$ given by $h_{t}(F)=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{n}\log\delta_{t}\left(G,F^{n}(G)% \right).$
